ormed the basis for the present work. Together, both volumes solidify Certeau’s place as a touchstone of twentieth-century literature and philosophy, and continue his exploration of the paradoxes of historiography; the construction of social reality through practice, testimony, and belief; the theorization of speech in angelology and glossolalia; and the interplay of prose and poetry in discourses of the ineffable. This book will be of vital interest to scholars in religious studies, theology, philosophy, history, and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMysticismzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aMysticismzEuropexHistoryy17th century. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  ahistoriography, social reality, mysticism, 16th century, 17th, religion, theology, history, testimony, belief, angelology, speech, glossolalia, prose, poetry, ineffable, nonfiction, philosophy, literature, nicholas of cusa, europe, silence, discourse, all seeing eye, knowledge, power, control, surveillance, individual, identity, fragment, melody, john cross, saint, holiness, graces, surin, spirituality, noise, madness, insanity, voice, richard simon, pascal, angels, saussure, language, communication, meaning, chiaroscuros.1 aGiard, Luce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmith, Michael B.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226209272423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226209272/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles